      "span_text": "Whether they are oriented to deliver an aggregated good (the sum of benefits received separately by many individuals) or a corporate good (experienced by whole communities or populations, such as herd immunity, reliable city-wide sanitation, or a safe and effective blood bank),  most public health interventions will readily satisfy the welfare-justification condition necessary to an accusation of paternalism."
